 To clean up the `macrokit/core` repository, we can use the following steps:

1. Close stale issues that have been inactive for more than a specified number of days (e.g., 30 days). This will help remove any open issues that are no longer relevant or need attention.

```yaml
{
  "name": "clean_up_repo",
  "arguments": {
    "owner": "macrokit",
    "repo": "core",
    "apply": true,
    "maxDaysOpen": 30,
    "excludeLabels": ["bug", "security", "pinned", "good first issue"]
  }
}
```

Result: The specified number of stale issues will be closed and a message confirming the number of closed issues will be displayed.

2. Suggest reviewers for any open pull requests in the repository to ensure that they receive proper attention from team members.

```yaml
{
  "name": "suggest_reviewers",
  "arguments": {
    "owner": "macrokit",
    "repo": "core"
  }
}
```

Result: A list of suggested reviewers for open pull requests will be displayed.

3. Generate release notes for the latest tag or branch in the repository to keep track of changes and updates.

```yaml
{
  "name": "generate_release_notes",
  "arguments": {
    "owner": "macrokit",
    "repo": "core",
    "base": "<previous_tag/branch>",
    "head": "main"
  }
}
```

Result: A markdown-formatted changelog of changes between the specified base and head will be displayed.

 To triage a pull request for the repository `vercel/next.js`, I will use the `triage_pull_request` macro. Here's the tool call:

```json
{
  "name": "triage_pull_request",
  "arguments": {
    "owner": "vercel",
    "repo": "next.js",
    "number": <PR number>,
    "apply": true
  }
}
```

Replace `<PR number>` with the number of the pull request you want to triage. The result will be a classification of the PR (bug/feature/docs/test/chore) and suggested labels based on its title and changed files. If the apply parameter is set to true, the suggested labels will also be applied to the PR.

 To triage the issue and suggest next steps for the failed GitHub Actions workflow run with ID 9999 in the golang/go repository, we can use the `capture_workflow_log` macro to view the rendered logs of the workflow run. After analyzing the logs, we may need to use the `triage_issue` or `triage_pull_request` macros depending on whether it's a pull request or an issue that caused the failure.

```
{
  "tool_calls": [
    {
      "name": "capture_workflow_log",
      "arguments": {
        "owner": "golang",
        "repo": "go",
        "runId": 9999
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "triage_issue" or "triage_pull_request",
      "arguments": {
        "owner": "golang",
        "repo": "go",
        // Use the appropriate number based on the captured workflow log analysis.
        "number": <PR_or_ISSUE_NUMBER>
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

After analyzing the logs and triaging the issue or pull request, we will provide a summary of the findings and suggested next steps for the user.

